	<title>Example Kanban Board</title>

	<content type="xhtml">
	<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
		<p>
			One thing often in usage with software development teams which employ <em>Kanban</em> is the <strong>Kanban board</strong>.
			Among other things, it helps visualize workflow.
		</p>
		<p>
			These can be physical or virtual.
			And each team may have a different board.
			Here I just document one board that worked for one team:
		</p>
		<br />
		<figure>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td style="border:1px solid black;padding:7pt;">
							Triage
						</td>
						<td style="border:1px solid black;padding:7pt;">
							Queued
						</td>
						<td style="border:1px solid black;padding:7pt;">
							Impeded While In Development
						</td>
						<td style="border:1px solid black;padding:7pt;">
							In Development
						</td>
						<td style="border:1px solid black;padding:7pt;">
							Ready For QA
						</td>
						<td style="border:1px solid black;padding:7pt;">
							Being QA'ed
						</td>
						<td style="border:1px solid black;padding:7pt;">
							Ready To Release
						</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
		</figure>
		<br />
		<p>
			Just a note that things typically jump from "<em>queued</em>" to "<em>in development</em>".
			But with the other states (excluding the "<em>impeded while in development</em>" state), it typically went from left-to-right, going from one column to the next.
		</p>


